Let’s KNOWLet’s KNOWSafety FirstUnit–III : Our Values11Accidents can happen at any place and at any time. They mostly happen due 
to our carelessness. At times, they can cause serious injuries.
We need to be aware and responsible for 
our own safety. We need to follow some 
safety rules so that accidents can be 
avoided.
Look at the given picture. All these are examples of accidents.
! Have you ever fallen and hurt yourself?
! Have you ever by mistake cut your finger with a blade or knife?
Safety on RoadsMajority of the accidents occur on roads. We need to be very cautious and follow 
the basic traffic rules.
! Do not run or play on the streets.
! Always cross the road at zebra crossing.
! Walk on a footpath.

! Do not push each other.

! Never fight with your schoolmates.
! If, you get hurt, inform your teacher or any other elder person. They will give you

Safety in SchoolSafety at Home
! Do not play with needles, blades, knives or any other sharp objects.
! Do not play with match sticks, near burning stoves or fire.
! Do not touch electric wires or points with wet hands. You may get an electric 
shock.
! Do not fly kites on an open terrace.
! Do not lean out over a railing.

(Knowledge)Safety protocols in Emergency SituationWe need to follow some safety tips in emergency situations such as fire, floods, 
earthquake, landslides etc.
Safety protocol for fire
! Switch off the gas regulator when not in use.
! Install smoke alarms at your homes/offices.
! Keep your heating instruments in check.
! Learn to use a fire extinguisher.
! In case of intense fire, inform fire station.
The emergency number of a fire station is 101.
Safety protocol for floods
 Overflow of water on land is called flood. It may happen due to heavy rains or 
any other natural disaster.
 In case of floods–
! Move immediately to higher ground area.
! Follow instructions from public safety officials.
! Never drive or walk through flood-water.
! Follow evacuation orders.
! Continue to check media for emergency informations.
EmergencyAn emergency is serious event that needs immediate action. e.g. fire, floods, 
earthquakes, landslides etc.
Environmental Studies-484

Safety protocol for earthquakesSudden shaking of earth's surface is called earthquake.
 During earthquake–
! Move away from buildings, electric wires and gas lines.
! Go to an open area away from trees, poles and buildings.
! Do not use the elevators/ lifts. The electricity may go out.
! If you are inside the home, drop down onto your hands and knees to protect 
yourself from falling.
! Cover your head and neck (and entire body if possible) underneath a sturdy 
table or a bed.
! Hold on to your shelter until the shaking stops.
Protocol For LandslidesThe rapid downslope movement of earth materials like rocks, debris and soil, is 
called landslide. 
 During a landslide–
! Stay calm and alert.
! Follow evacuation orders and instruction from the local authorities.
! Move to higher grounds.
! Stay away from steep slopes or hill sides.
! Curl into a ball and protect your head if escape is not possible.
! Assemble an emergency kit having packaged food, water, first-aid material, flash 
light, blankets etc. Keep the kit in a readily accessible place.
! Determine safe areas on your property or nearby to seek shelter in a landslide.
Emergency ServicesEmergency services are organisations that ensure public safety, security and 
health during emergencies.
Fire station– During emergency situations, apart from fire fighting, the 
department also undertakes rescue operations and saves people trapped in debris 
of fallen buildings, caught in floods or land slides.
Environmental Studies-485

(Knowledge)Hospitals– During emergency situations–
! Hospitals take necessary actions to control crowd and traffic within the hospital. 
They maintain a register for victims of disaster.
! Provide necessary instructions to patients & their relatives.
! Qualified emergency doctors and nurses provide emergent care to save lines of 
victims.
The emergency number for Ambulance service is 102.
Police stations– The primary role of police during disasters is Search and Rescue 
(SAR) which includes–
! To identify and assist those who are in need of help.
! To supply relief materials like food and water to the people trapped in disaster.
! To arrange for proper medical treatment to the injured individuals.
! To stop people from taking advantage of the situation.
The emergency number for Police Station is 100.
Ethical Use of MediaDuring emergency, media plays an important role. Some of the points are–
! Quickly sends out alerts.
! Shares updates and safety tips.
! Provides rapid feedback from the witnesses of the event.
! Transmit requests for help.

Let’s KNOWLet’s KNOWIndia : A Land of 
Rich CultureUnit–III : Our Values12StarterIndia is a land of rich culture and heritage. People in different states speak 
different languages, eat different foods and celebrate different festivals. The 
diverse languages, customs, dresses, music, dances and religious beliefs are 
part of the Indian Culture and make India a unique country.
! Write the names of these festivals in the given spaces.
! Which state of India does each of these festivals belong to?
LanguagesDifferent languages are spoken in different parts of our country. Hindi is the official 
language of the country. There are 22 languages recognized by the constitution of 
India which are used as the official language at the state level. These are—
1. Assamese, 2.Bangla, 3. Bodo, 4, Dogri, 5. Gujarati, 6. Hindi, 7. Kannada, 8. 
Kashmiri, 9. Konkani, 10. Maithili, 11. Malyalam, 12. Manipuri, 13. Marathi, 14.

Telugu, 22. Urdu.
DressesThe regional diversity of India is found in the dresses worn by the people of 
different regions. The traditional costumes of men and women are different in 
most of the states.
Though saree is the most popular dress worn by the women of India, it is worn in 
different styles in different regions. The other popular dress worn by the women of 
northern India is Salwar Kameez.
The ghagra-choli is worn by the women in Rajasthan. The traditional dress worn by 
women in Haryana is Daman kurti and Chadder.
The traditional dress of men in India are dhoti-kurta, kurta-pyjama or lungi and a 
turban or cap.
These days men and women also wear trousers, shirts, jeans and T-shirts.
Sanskrit and Tamil are two of the oldest languages of the world.
FoodJust as people in different parts of India speak different languages, they also enjoy 
eating different types of cuisines.
Rajma-chawal, chhole-bhature and shahi paneer are popular in North India. Fish 
curry and rice are eaten in eastern states (Bihar, West Bengal, Odisha etc etc.)Dal-bati-churma is enjoyed by the people in 
Rajasthan. Gujarat is famous for dhokla, 
thepla and khandvi while sambar-idli and 
dosa are popular in south India.
Generally, the staple food of people of a state 
is what grows in that region. Wheat, rice and 
millets are the main staple food of Indians. 
Different types of vegetables and

A variety of spices are grown in India. 
They add flavour and colour to the food.

(Knowledge)Music has always been a part of Indian culture. Indian classical music is divided into 
two styles.
 1. Hindustani Music 
 
2. 
Carnatic MusicHindustani Music developed in the northern part of India while carnatic music 
developed in the southern part.
Both the styles of music are based on a combination of raga and tala. Each raga is 
sung at a particular time according to the specific season and occasion, while tala is 
the beat of music.
Hindutani music comprises of thumri, tappa, ghazal, khayal and dhrupada styles. 
The famous singers of Hindustani music were Tansen, Haridas and Baiju Bawra.
Carnatic music gives importance to bhakti and devotion.
MusicTansen was one of the nine gems in Akbar's court. He composed and sang 
many ragas like raga Deepak, which could light diyas and raga Megh-Malhar, which could bring rain.

Let’s KNOWLet’s KNOWStarterWe Need Each-OtherUnit–IV : Our Values13Man is a social animal who can not live alone. Right from ancient times, he 
has lived in groups and communities. Community members cooperate with 
each other and share work and duties. When we look around, we find many 
people who help us in our daily lives. They make our lives comfortable and 
easy.
! Who grows food for you? 
___________
! Who treats you when you are sick? 
___________
! Who makes furniture for your houses? 
___________
Different Kinds of WorkPeople do different kinds of jobs to earn money. Any job that a person does to earn 
money is called an occupation or profession.
Skilled and Unskilled Work– A skill is the ability to do a task well. Some jobs do not 
need any training by experts. These jobs are called unskilled work. They are 
learned through observation and practice. Many jobs require special training 
Environmental Studies-498

which is imparted by expert faculties at colleges and institutes. Students receive 
degrees and diplomas after successful completion of their training. 
Let us know about some people who help us to live a comfortable life.
FarmerDayaram is farmer. His occupation is farming. He 
grow different types of food grains, vegetables and 
fruits. He ploughs the field, sows the seeds and 
harvests the crop. By selling his crop in the market, 
he helps us to get our food and at the same time, 
earns money for his family. He learnt this work from 
his father and grandfather.
CarpenterRajesh is a carpenter. He makes wooden 
furniture and doors, windows and other fitting 
for buildings. We all need these things. He learnt 
this work from his father. 
TailorPrem is a tailor. He stitches beautiful dresses 
using a sewing machine. He learnt this work from 
his father.
WashermanRamu is a washerman. He washes our clothes 
and irons them. He learnt this work with regular 
practice.
Environmental Studies-499

PotterBaldev is a potter. He makes beautiful earthen 
pots on potter's wheel. His wife makes 
beautiful designs on these pots. His 
grandfather taught him this beautiful craft.
WeaverRafiq is a weaver. He weaves clothes on a loom. 
He learnt this work from his uncle.
EmbroidererSonali is an embroiderer. She makes attractive 
designs on ladies suits and sarees with a needle 
and thread. She learnt this art from her mother.
DoctorDr. Rakesh Singh is a doctor. He treats sick 
people. He got his training and a degree from a 
medical college.
EngineerMr. Sachin Dubey is an engineer. He got his training 
and a degree from an engineering college. He make 
blueprints for building, bridges, roads, houses etc.
Environmental Studies-4100

Factory WorkersMany people in cities work in different factories. 
They mostly work with machines that they have 
been trained to handle. They work in industries like 
textile mills, steel plants, sugar mills, plastic goods 
factories etc.
Voluntary WorkSome jobs are voluntary. People in such jobs do not always earn money but work to 
help others. The duties carried out by the people working in NGOs are examples of 
such jobs.
Gender Equality in JobsEarlier, only men worked to earn money while women looked after the house and 
children. But, the things have changed now. Women too work as teachers, doctors, 
nurses, pilots, soldiers, astronauts etc. It is good to see women and men being 
treated equal in the job space.
